					   <td>

			
			
			


<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">
<tr>
	<td width="1%">&nbsp;</td>
	<td width="98%">

		<table width="100%">
		<tr>
			<td>
				<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="3"><b>    Ultimate tailoring guide for the aspiring tailor: Part I</b></font>
					<br>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">
					<b><A href="mailto:TREKKER789@aol.com">ArdenD</a> | 
		            6/22/1999 9:49:26 PM</b></font></p>
		         <a href="guides.asp">
		         <font face="verdana" size="2">Return to guide listing.</font></a>
					
					<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">Hey, this is Sladek from the Tunare server. I am here for one purpose (for now) and that is to teach you how to make some quick money at the earlier levels (from levels 3-8) and gain a trade skill as well! This trade skill is tailoring. The skill is frowned upon by some because of it's near to impossibility to get to a level which is worthwhile at higher levels to make better equipment (I will delve into that issue later when I write my next guide) but indeed this skill can be used and abused to make money (less and less important the higher you get) and have some dinero to afford some of the better armor earlier on in the game, not to mention being able to make your own armor depending on what class you are!<BR>
<BR>
First of all, you should have a character at or about level 2 in an area where pelts are readily available off enemies. (Kelethin is a great area, especially if you're a ranger and can track black wolves). Freeport will not satisfy you as you will not be able to get alot of pelts until the levels 4-6 (from E. commonlands). Q'eynos is fine too, since I know a low level enemy there drops ruined cat pelts, and if you're in Q'eynos, chances are you can make armor with that you can wear (although I don't know this from personal experience).<BR>
The reason I said it's better to be a higher level to start tailoring is because of the starting cost, which is a whopping 6g or so for a small sewing kit! (I know, I know, but for a lower level character, this is humongous).<BR>
<BR>
The components you will need are the small sewing kit, the tailoring book (not found in all areas, and not needed, but rumored to give you a higher level of success if held while practicing) which costs a bit over 1g, an appropriate pelt and an appropriate pattern.<BR>
<BR>
I will base this assuming you were a wood elf ranger starting in kelethin, but you could have very easily made a high elf cleric and follow the same instructions.<BR>
<BR>
First, buy the sewing kit and tailoring book (recommended, not needed), then go kill a black wolf and find yourself a RUINED wolf pelt. Wolf pelts make small sized PATCHWORK (which is what is made using RUINED quality pelts) a decent armor for levels ranging from 1-8 and possibly up to 10 or more for classes who cannot wear anything in a higher class than leather yet can't afford magical armor.<BR>
<BR>
Go to your nearest tailoring shop (tent if it's kelethin -- up from the main lift [I'm pretty sure] across 2 bridges there should be a person selling patterns and the sewing kit, and maybe the tailoring book as well, don't take my word on this, if you can't find the shop, ask around, people should point you in the correct direction) and buy the pattern of armor you wish to make, whether it be a tunic, boots, leggings, or just a gorget. (I recommend gorgets for the first 5 levels if you didn't dump that many practice points into it to start)<BR>
<BR>
Open your sewing kit, put the RUINED wolf pelt (or other type, depending where you are hunting) and the appropriate pattern, and click on COMBINE. You will then get an appropriate message telling you what has happened. Either you suceeded or failed, unlike some other trade skills, tailoring doesn't give you any items on failure.<BR>
<BR>
Don't be discouraged if you failed on all your attempts up to this point, and only gained a few skill levels, this is common and almost necessary in building any trade skill. You will eventually succeed and you will have made some PATCHWORK! Most pieces of patchwork sell to people around the average price of 2g a piece (inflation and deflation nowadays, I can't even follow the market anymore) and full sets go for around 1p - 1.2p (A full set consists of all 7 pieces which you can create) Although, if you are impatient and wish to get your money back fast (which is what is great about building this skill) you can sell back your patchwork to the shops for about 1.2g (more or less) and use that money to buy yourself a couple more patterns. If after many trials you see you have succeeded about 50% of the time, math will obviously show you that you are not losing money if you just sell back to the stores, yet you can sell to people and make a PROFIT! At levels 15-26 you don't see much a difference in how much you succeed or fail, it varies from 50%-85% depending on how good you are, yet you rarely ever lose money on this investment.<BR>
<BR>
After you have maxed your skill at 26 (after which making patchwork is trivial for your level, which means you gain no more skill making it) you almost certainly even make a profit selling patchwork back to the shops themselves, although so small, it is not worth pursuing unless you are a character with a high charisma and get nearer to 1.4g a piece at the shops.<BR>
<BR>
I know this is a lot of information to digest, but this is all you need to know about making a tailor, and maxing your trade skill at 26. After this, you will need to make higher level armor (studded, re-inforced leather, backpacks, quivers) but I will get into that next part.<BR>
<BR>
Any questions? Comments? Praises? All mail is welcome: TREKKER789@aol.com<BR>
<BR>
Arden Daghlian<BR>
aka<BR>
Sladek (Tunare server)<BR>
<BR>
Peace
			<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
					</p>
			</td>
